.TH OVERRIDE 1 "July 2026" "override 1.2.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
override \- securely destroy files with crypto-shredding, multi-pass overwrites, and self-resilience
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B override
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.IR PATH ...
.br
.B override
.RB [ \-\-prompt ]
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.br
.B override
.BI \-\-wipe\-free " DIR"
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B override
securely destroys files so their content cannot be recovered. The default
destruction pipeline applied to every target is:
.IP 1. 4
encrypt (crypto-shred: encrypt in place, then discard the key)
.IP 2. 4
random overwrite (phase A)
.IP 3. 4
null (zero) overwrite
.IP 4. 4
random overwrite (phase B)
.IP 5. 4
rename to random name(s)
.IP 6. 4
delete (unlink)
.PP
Every write is flushed and fsync'd. The encryption key is generated with a
CSPRNG, used once, and zeroized immediately \(em it is never written or printed.
.PP
.B Note:
on SSDs and copy-on-write filesystems (btrfs, ZFS, ...) a logical write may not
reach the original physical blocks. This limits the in-place crypto-shred just
as much as the overwrite passes, so neither assures destruction on such media.
See the shipped documentation in
.I /usr/share/doc/override-tool
for details.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-prompt
Read one or more target paths interactively from stdin, one per line, until a
blank line or EOF. Paths read this way are never passed as arguments, so they do
not appear in shell history. Command-line paths are still processed.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Print detailed progress for every file, phase and pass.
.TP
.B \-\-dry\-run
Show what would be destroyed without touching anything.
.TP
.BR \-r ", " \-\-recursive
Recurse into directories and process every file inside.
.TP
.BR \-e ", " \-\-encryption " \fIN\fR"
Number of encryption (crypto-shred) passes. 0 disables the phase. Default: 1.
.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-iterations " \fIN\fR"
Number of random-data overwrite passes, applied in both random rounds. 0
disables random overwrite. Default: 1.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-null " \fIN\fR"
Number of zero-fill overwrite passes. 0 disables the null phase. Default: 1.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-verify
Skip read-back verification of the encryption pass (faster, less safe).
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-source " \fIPATH\fR"
File used as the source of bytes for overwrite passes, read in a streaming,
wrap-around fashion. Defaults to the OS CSPRNG. A predictable or low-entropy
source weakens the overwrite guarantee and is not recommended.
.TP
.BR \-u ", " \-\-rename " \fIN\fR"
Number of times to rename the file to a random name before deletion. Default: 1.
.TP
.BR \-o ", " \-\-order " \fIsequential\fR|\fIbatch\fR"
Processing order when multiple targets are given. Defaults to
.I sequential
(or
.I batch
under \-\-no\-stop).
.TP
.B \-\-no\-stop
Keep overwriting the targets until interrupted, then delete them. Each file is
crypto-shredded and renamed up front, then looped over random/null/random until
an interrupt arrives. A second interrupt forces immediate exit.
.TP
.BI \-\-wipe\-free " PATH"
Wipe the free space of the filesystem containing the given directory instead of
destroying files. Temporarily fills the volume to 100%. Pointing it at the
root/system filesystem is refused unless
.B \-\-force
is given. As a non-root user on ext2/3/4 the reserved blocks (default ~5%) are
not allocated, so that fraction of free space is not wiped; run as root or lower
the reserve first (\fBtune2fs \-m 0\fR). Cannot be combined with file targets.
.TP
.B \-\-force
Override safety guards. Currently: permit
.B \-\-wipe\-free
on the root/system filesystem.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print help.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Print version.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B override secret.txt
Run the default pipeline on one file.
.TP
.B override -v -r ./olddir
Recursively destroy a directory, verbosely.
.TP
.B override -e 2 -i 3 -n 1 a.bin b.bin
Two encryption, three random, one null pass.
.TP
.B override -i 0 -e 0 -n 3 log.txt
Null-only wipe (no encryption/random).
.TP
.B override --no-stop -u 5 target.dat
Emergency: encrypt+rename now, loop, delete on Ctrl-C.
.SH EXIT STATUS
Returns 0 on success and non-zero if any target could not be processed.
.SH SECURITY
Recovery resistance depends on the underlying storage. On copy-on-write
filesystems and flash storage (SSDs, USB sticks, SD cards) with wear-leveling, a
write may not hit the original blocks \(em and because the plaintext already
exists on the media, the in-place crypto-shred is limited exactly as the
overwrite passes are, so neither can assure destruction there. Prefer full-disk
encryption, ATA/NVMe secure-erase, or physical destruction. See
.I /usr/share/doc/override-tool/security.md.gz
and
.I filesystems.md.gz.
